<h2 id="simple-summary">
<a href="#simple-summary" class="anchor-link"></a> Simple Summary
</h2>
<p>Adds an opcode that gives the EVM access to the block’s base fee.</p>
<h2 id="abstract">
<a href="#abstract" class="anchor-link"></a> Abstract
</h2>
<p>Add a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BASEFEE (0x48)</code> that returns the value of the base fee of the current block it is executing in.</p>
<h2 id="motivation">
<a href="#motivation" class="anchor-link"></a> Motivation
</h2>
<p>The intended use case would be for contracts to get the value of the base fee. This feature would enable or improve existing use cases, such as:</p>
<ul>
<li>Contracts that need to set bounties for anyone to “poke” them with a transaction could set the bounty to be <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BASEFEE + x</code>, or <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BASEFEE * (1 + x)</code>. This makes the mechanism more reliable, because they will always pay “enough” regardless of market conditions.</li>
<li>Gas futures can be implemented based on it. This would be more precise than gastokens.</li>
<li>Improve the security for state channels, plasma, optirolls and other fraud proof driven solutions. Having the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BASEFEE</code> as an input allows you to lengthen the challenge period automatically if you see that the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BASEFEE</code> is high.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="specification">
<a href="#specification" class="anchor-link"></a> Specification
</h2>
<p>Add a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BASEFEE</code> opcode at <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">(0x48)</code>, with gas cost <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">G_base</code>.</p>
